results.reasoning: Ultrasound shows a thin central uterine septum dividing a single uterine cavity into two hemicavities with placenta implanted on the septum. External contour and thin internal septum favour a septate uterus rather than bicornuate or didelphys; this represents a gravid septate uterus with septal placental implantation.

Chronic left lumbar pain, long-standing anemia and leukocytosis with imaging showing enlarged non-functioning kidney with multiple low-density areas and staghorn calculus, consistent with diffuse xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis.
Pineal/tectal midline enhancing mass in a male causing obstructive hydrocephalus with excellent response to radiotherapy — classic for a radiosensitive intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma).

Postoperative CT-urography demonstrates extravasation of excreted contrast from the distal ureter with pooling in the pelvis (axial and 3D reconstructions), consistent with an iatrogenic intraoperative ureteral injury with urinoma.

Well-defined, multiloculated T2-hyperintense cystic lesion at the volar wrist adjacent to tendon sheath/joint — imaging appearance is characteristic of a ganglion cyst; other choices are solid fibrous lesions with low T2 signal (GCTTS, fibroma) or nodular fasciitis/fibrous histiocytoma which are typically solid and enhancing).

Cystic lesion in left upper quadrant shows double-wall/gut-signature on ultrasound and a well-defined fluid-filled mass adjacent to bowel on CT with surrounding inflammatory changes and patient febrile—most consistent with an infected enteric duplication cyst.

Transverse sagittal ultrasound demonstrates a thin midline uterine septum dividing the endometrial cavity into two hemicavities with the placenta implanted on the left side — classic for a gravid septate uterus with septal placental implantation. Bicornuate/didelphys would show external fundal cleft or separate uterine bodies rather than a thin central septum; arcuate is only a shallow indentation and synechiae are usually focal.

Chronic symptoms with anemia and leukocytosis plus imaging consistent with enlarged, non-functioning kidney with multiple low-attenuation dilated calyces (bear-paw appearance), staghorn calculi and perinephric inflammatory change — classic for diffuse xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis.

Homogeneously enhancing, relatively hyperdense pineal region mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus with excellent radiotherapy response and biopsy confirmation — classic for intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma).

Excretory-phase CT demonstrates a pelvic fluid collection that opacifies with contrast and a visible tract/contrast leak from the distal ureter on axial and 3D images, consistent with iatrogenic ureteral injury producing a urinoma.

MRI shows a well-defined fluid-filled volar cystic lesion with homogeneous T2 hyperintensity and only peripheral/rim enhancement, consistent with a ganglion cyst. There is no low-signal hemosiderin or marked solid enhancement to suggest GCTTS/FTS, and the imaging appearance is not typical for fibrous histiocytoma or nodular fasciitis.

CT and US show a cystic mesenteric lesion in the left flank with peripheral wall enhancement, possible thin internal septa, surrounding fat stranding and hyperemia on Doppler in a febrile patient with leukocytosis. These findings are most consistent with an inflamed/infected mesenteric lymphangioma. Enteric duplication would show a gut-signature/shared bowel wall; pseudocyst lacks pancreatitis history; mesothelial cysts are usually simple. Therefore A.
